1. PROTOCOL IDENTITY AND MANDATE

1.1 WHAT IS GIOP
GIOP is the unified, formula-defined imaging protocol. It is the single
canonical source of truth for every mathematical transform, optical DNA
sequence, sensor characteristic, display model, and neural rendering
method in modern imaging. GIOP is not an application, library, or codec.
It is the auditable knowledge base from which all imaging software,
firmware, and hardware derive their correctness.

1.2 WHY GIOP EXISTS
Professional imaging suffers from three fatal conditions.
Interoperability collapse: ARRI, RED, and Sony cameras speak mutually
  unintelligible color languages. GIOP is the Rosetta Stone that maps
  every sensor to a common linear space.
Inconsistency: a look created in one DI suite renders differently in
  another. GIOP guarantees a pixel from any source is visually identical
  on any reference display.
Incomprehension: artists and engineers lack a single verified reference
  for anamorphic streak wavelengths, inverse log formulas, or perceptual
  transform design. GIOP provides that reference.

1.3 HOW GIOP WORKS
Every frame follows a verifiable chain of trust. The photon enters the
lens, is converted to electrons, linearized through an IDT, compensated
optically, placed in a scene-referred working space, transformed by
artistic intent, rendered for a specific display via an ODT, and finally
emitted as light. Every arrow in this chain is governed by an immutable,
hash-referenced formula stored in the Library.

1.4 WHERE GIOP IS DEPLOYED
Color correction: DaVinci Resolve DCTL engine, Baselight BLG stack.
Compositing: Nuke STMap and Python API, Flame Batch.
Virtual production: Unreal Engine Pixel Streaming, LED volume genlock.
Hardware: firmware lookup matrices in smart cameras and mastering monitors.
Streaming and broadcast: encoding pipelines, QC automation, IMF packaging.

1.5 WHO OPERATES GIOP
The protocol is designed for imaging scientists, pipeline technical
directors, VFX compositors, colorists, DITs, camera engineers, and
anyone who requires pixel-level mathematical certainty in image
processing.

1.6 WHAT PROBLEM GIOP SOLVES
Death of the black box LUT: replaces non-editable vendor LUTs with open,
verifiable mathematical linearization.
AI poisoning resistance: training data is always GIOP-linearized, preventing
the ingestion of incorrect gamma curves or mismatrixed wide-gamut material.
Preservation: a GIOP sequence is mathematically guaranteed to be correctly
restorable in one hundred years, independent of any defunct software
application.

2. THE TWELVE KINGDOMS

2.1 KINGDOM 00 — SCIENCE OF LIGHT
Nature of light, electromagnetic spectrum, radiometry, photometry, spectral
power distribution, surface-light interaction (BRDF, BSSRDF), light
transport and volumetric scattering.

2.2 KINGDOM 01 — HUMAN VISION VS CAMERA AND LENS
Human visual system (rods, cones, luminance adaptation), Weber-Fechner law,
dynamic range gap between eye and sensor, spectral sensitivity mismatch,
tone mapping operators, color appearance models, and the perception-driven
design of OETF and EOTF.

2.3 KINGDOM 02 — FUNDAMENTAL IMAGING PHYSICS AND SENSOR METROLOGY
Photon statistics, shot noise, read noise, SNR, exposure theory, saturation-
based ISO, dual native ISO mathematical model, photometric and radiometric
units, geometric invariance.

2.4 KINGDOM 03 — COLOR SCIENCE AND VISUAL PERCEPTION
ACES 2.0 framework, gamut compression algorithms, Dolby Vision 2.0 and
ST.2084 PQ, advanced color metrics (CIEDE2000, CAM16-UCS, ICTCP, JzAzBz),
camera color science DNA, spectral LUT and 31-band modeling, white point
adaptation, skin tone preservation and color fairness.

2.5 KINGDOM 04 — PHYSICS AND MATHEMATICS FOR IMAGING
Advanced PBR theory (Cook-Torrance, GGX, Schlick Fresnel), wave optics
(diffraction, interference, polarization), geometric optics (Snell's law,
lens maker's equation), statistical image analysis, multi-bounce illumination,
energy conservation, geometric invariance, Fourier analysis, spectral
rendering, biological face lock, fabric relighting, subsurface scattering,
inverse pipeline linearization.

2.6 KINGDOM 05 — SENSOR, LENS HARDWARE AND ISP PIPELINE
Sensor metrology (QE, FWC, conversion gain, dynamic range), ISP pipeline
architecture and stage definitions, lens hardware (vignetting, distortion,
breathing), stabilization models (OIS, gimbal PID, AI horizon lock),
sensor-lens interaction models.

2.7 KINGDOM 06 — AI FOUNDATION
CNN fundamentals, Transformer attention for image restoration, diffusion
models, generative adversarial networks, AI-native ISP pipelines, AI color
grading, generative video and film production, AI standards and certification,
ethics and content authenticity, training data requirements and bias mitigation.

2.8 KINGDOM 07 — NEURAL FOUNDATION
Neural Radiance Fields (NeRF), 3D Gaussian Splatting (3DGS), neural
supersampling and denoising (DLSS Ray Reconstruction), neural video
compression, 4D dynamic neural representations, neural materials and textures.

2.9 KINGDOM 08 — VIDEO ENGINEERING AND BROADCAST STANDARDS
VVC, AV1, and AV2 compression tools (CCLM, affine motion, MTS), rate-
distortion optimization, video quality metrics (PSNR, SSIM, VMAF), SMPTE
timecode and genlock, ST 2110 IP transport, HDR broadcast practices and
codec-aware color management.

2.10 KINGDOM 09 — IMMERSIVE FORMATS AND METADATA STANDARDS
ACESclip and ACES Metadata File (AMF), Multiview HEVC for stereo and multi-
view, Dolby Vision dynamic metadata XML (ST 2094-10), general immersive
metadata schema.

2.11 KINGDOM 10 — IMMERSIVE AND VOLUMETRIC CAPTURE
MPEG-I Visual and 6DoF standards, volumetric video capture pipelines,
dynamic 3D Gaussian Splatting (4DGS), physics-aware volumetric reconstruction
(PAVR), light-field capture and rendering, point cloud processing and
compression (V-PCC, G-PCC).

2.12 KINGDOM 11 — SPATIAL COMPUTING
Head-mounted display architectures and rendering parameters, foveated
rendering and transport, varifocal and light-field HMDs, real-time cloud
rendering (CloudXR), spatial color appearance and passthrough matching,
timewarp and synchronization, holographic and holoportation displays.

